7 SECTION 2.(d) G.S. 50-20, as amended by subsection (c) of this section, reads as
8 rewritten:
9 "§ 50-20. Distribution by court of marital and divisible property.
10 (a) Upon application of a party, the court shall determine what is the marital property and
11 divisible property and shall provide for an equitable distribution of the marital property and
12 divisible property between the parties in accordance with the provisions of this section.
13 (b) For purposes of this section:section, the following definitions apply:
14 (1) "Distributive award" means payments Distributive award. – Payments that are
15 payable either in a lump sum or over a period of time in fixed amounts, but
16 shall the term does not include alimony payments or other similar payments
17 for support and maintenance which are treated as ordinary income to the
18 recipient under the Internal Revenue Code.or maintenance of a spouse or
19 child.
20 (1a) "Divisible property" means all Divisible property. – All real and personal
21 property as set forth below:
22 a. All appreciation and diminution in value of marital property and
23 divisible property of the parties occurring after the date of separation
24 and prior to the date of distribution, except that appreciation or
25 diminution in value which that is the result of postseparation actions
26 or activities of a spouse shall not be is not treated as divisible property.
27 b. All property, property rights, or any portion thereof received after the
28 date of separation but before the date of distribution that was acquired
29 as a result of the efforts of either spouse during the marriage and before
30 the date of separation, including, but not limited to, commissions,
31 bonuses, and contractual rights.
32 c. Passive income from marital property received after the date of
33 separation, including, but not limited to, interest and dividends.
34 d. Passive increases and passive decreases in marital debt and financing
35 charges and interest related to marital debt.
36 (1b) "Marital property" means all Marital property. – All real and personal property
37 acquired by either spouse or both spouses during the course of the marriage
38 and before the date of the separation of the parties, and presently owned,
39 except property determined to be separate property or divisible property in
40 accordance with subdivision (2) or (4) of this subsection. Marital property
41 includes all vested and nonvested pension, retirement, and other pension and
42 retirement rights and benefits, vested and nonvested deferred compensation
43 rights, rights and benefits, and vested and nonvested military pensions eligible
44 under the federal Uniformed Services Former Spouses Protection Act. It is
45 presumed that all property acquired after the date of marriage and before the
46 date of separation is marital property except property which that is separate
47 property under subdivision (2) of this subsection. It is presumed that all real
48 property creating a tenancy by the entirety acquired after the date of marriage
49 and before the date of separation is marital property. Either presumption may
50 be rebutted by the greater weight of the evidence.
