21 (c) There shall be an equal division by using net value of marital property and net value
22 of divisible property unless the court determines that an equal division is not equitable. If the
23 court determines that an equal division is not equitable, the court shall divide the marital property
24 and divisible property equitably. The court shall consider all of the following factors under this
25 subsection:
26 (1) The income, property, and liabilities of each party at the time the division of
27 property is to become effective.
28 (2) Any obligation for support arising out of a prior marriage.
29 (3) The duration of the marriage and the age and physical and mental health of
30 both parties.
31 (4) The need of a parent with custody of a child or children of the marriage to
32 occupy or own the marital residence and to use or own its household effects.
33 (5) The expectation of pension, retirement, or other deferred compensation rights
34 that are not marital property.
35 (6) Any equitable claim to, interest in, or direct or indirect contribution made to
36 the acquisition of such the marital property by the party not having title,
37 including joint efforts or expenditures and contributions and services, or lack
38 thereof, as a spouse, parent, wage earner earner, or homemaker.
39 (7) Any direct or indirect contribution made by one spouse to help educate or
40 develop the career potential of the other spouse.
41 (8) Any direct contribution to an increase in value of separate property which that
42 occurs during the course of the marriage.
43 (9) The liquid or nonliquid character of all marital property and divisible property.
44 (10) The difficulty of evaluating any component asset or any interest in a business,
45 corporation corporation, or profession, and the economic desirability of
46 retaining such the asset or interest, intact and free from any claim or
47 interference by the other party.
48 (11) The tax consequences to each party, including those federal and State tax
49 consequences that would have been incurred if the marital and divisible
50 property had been sold or liquidated on the date of valuation. The trial court
51 may, however, in its discretion, consider whether or when such the tax
