1 (h) If either party claims that any real property is marital property or divisible property,
2 that party may cause a notice of lis pendens to be recorded pursuant to Article 11 of Chapter 1 of
3 the General Statutes. Any person whose conveyance or encumbrance is recorded or whose
4 interest is obtained by descent, prior to the filing of the lis pendens, shall take takes the real
5 property free of any claim resulting from the equitable distribution proceeding. The court may
6 cancel the notice of lis pendens upon substitution of a bond with surety in an amount determined
7 by the court to be sufficient provided the court finds that the claim of the spouse against property
8 subject to the notice of lis pendens can be satisfied by money damages.
9 (i) Upon filing an action or motion in the cause requesting an equitable distribution or
10 alleging that an equitable distribution will be requested when it is timely to do so, a party may
11 seek injunctive relief pursuant to G.S. 1A-1, Rule 65 Rule 65, and Chapter 1, Article 37, Article
12 37 of Chapter 1 of the General Statutes to prevent the disappearance, waste waste, or conversion
13 of property alleged to be marital property, divisible property, or separate property of the party
14 seeking relief. The court, in lieu of granting an injunction, may require a bond or other assurance
15 of sufficient amount to protect the interest of the other spouse in the property. Upon application
16 by the owner of separate property which that was removed from the marital home or possession
17 of its owner by the other spouse, the court may enter an order for reasonable counsel fees and
18 costs of court incurred to regain its possession, but such the fees shall not exceed the fair market
19 value of the separate property at the time it was removed.
20 (i1) Unless good cause is shown that there should not be an interim distribution, the court
21 may, at any time after an action for equitable distribution has been filed and prior to the final
22 judgment of equitable distribution, enter orders an order declaring what is separate property and
23 may also enter orders an order dividing part of the marital property, divisible property or debt, or
24 marital debt between the parties. The partial distribution may provide for a distributive award
25 and may also provide for a distribution of marital property, marital debt, divisible property, or
26 divisible debt. Any such orders entered shall be taken into consideration at trial and shall be given
27 proper credit given.credit.
28 Hearings held pursuant to this subsection may be held at sessions arranged by the chief
29 district court judge pursuant to G.S. 7A-146 and, if held at such these sessions, shall are not be
30 subject to the reporting requirements of G.S. 7A-198.
31 (j) In any order for the distribution of property made pursuant to this section, the court
32 shall make written findings of fact that support the determination that the marital property and
33 divisible property has been equitably divided.
34 (k) The rights of the parties to an equitable distribution of marital property and divisible
35 property are a species of common ownership, the rights of the respective parties vesting at the
36 time of the parties' separation.
37 (l) The following applies regarding the death of a spouse:
38 (1) A claim for equitable distribution, whether an action is filed or not, survives
39 the death of a spouse so long as the parties are living separate and apart at the
40 time of death.
41 (2) The provisions of Article 19 of Chapter 28A of the General Statutes shall be
42 is applicable to a claim for equitable distribution against the estate of the
43 deceased spouse.
44 (3) Any claim for equitable distribution against the surviving spouse made by the
45 estate of the deceased spouse must shall be filed with the district court within
46 one year of the date of death of the deceased spouse or be forever barred."
47 SECTION 2.(e) G.S. 39-13.3(a)(1) and G.S. 41-63(4)a., as enacted by this section
48 regarding an elective life estate, apply to conveyances executed before, on, or after the effective
49 date of this act. The remainder of this section applies to conveyances executed on or after the
50 effective date of this act.
51 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
